SIMPLE: spanker
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spanker
<hw>Spank"er</hw> <pr>(sp⟦acr⟧⟦nsm⟧k"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>One who spanks, or anything used as an instrument for
spanking.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The after sail of a ship or bark,
being a fore-and-aft sail attached to a boom and gaff; -- sometimes
called <altname>driver</altname>. See <xex>Illust.</xex> under
<er>Sail</er>.</def> <rj><au>Totten.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who takes long, quick strides in walking; also,
a fast horse.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Something very large, or larger than common; a
whopper, as a stout or tall person.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Spanker boom</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a boom to
which a spanker sail is attached. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of
<er>Ship</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spanker</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spanker
<hw>Spank"er</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A small coin.</def> <mark>[Obs. or
Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>spanking</ent>⟦br⟧
